{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"eb616244-b4d9-48ca-a0b0-3b5a52807473","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, the OS automatically generates a **`.ips` crash report**. You can find it in:\n\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\n\nor the system-wide location:\n\n```\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\n\nLook for a file named like `YourAppName_<date>_<machine>.ips`. You can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them.\n\nSince `createdump` is not bundled with NativeAOT apps, these OS-level `.ips` reports are your primary crash artifact. If you need to **symbolicate** the native frames in that `.ips` file (e.g., resolve `libcoreclr` addresses to .NET runtime source lines), I can help with that too — just say the word.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c152f200-6e4c-4b2f-9704-9e69119e451e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a diagnostic question — let me check if any of my available skills are relevant.\n\nThe `dump-collect` skill is about configuring and collecting crash dumps for modern .NET applications, and the `apple-crash-symbolication` skill is about symbolicating Apple crash logs. The `dump-collect` skill seems most relevant for the collection question, though the `apple-crash-symbolication` skill mentions retrieving .ips crash logs.\n\nLet me answer this directly since it's a straightforward knowledge question.","outputTokens":363,"requestId":"2047:A917E:6E5BD6:80DF67:69F01193"},"id":"2e5e9bb0-8488-48c2-af05-816fcaed4f5d","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:47:11.100Z","parentId":"5163967a-1630-47c4-b377-0aa83412a157"}
